# Spring Boot 3 Cursor Rules

## Architecture
- Follow layered architecture: Controller → Service → Repository
- Use constructor injection (not field injection with `@Autowired`)
- Keep controllers thin — delegate to service layer
- Use DTOs for API request/response, entities for persistence

## REST API
- Use `@RestController` for API endpoints
- Return `ResponseEntity<T>` for explicit HTTP status codes
- Use `@Valid` with Bean Validation annotations for input validation
- Follow REST conventions: GET (read), POST (create), PUT (update), DELETE (remove)
- Use `@ExceptionHandler` / `@ControllerAdvice` for global error handling

## JPA & Database
- Use Spring Data JPA repositories (`JpaRepository<T, ID>`)
- Define entities with `@Entity`, IDs with `@Id @GeneratedValue`
- Use `@Transactional` on service methods (not repository)
- Avoid N+1 queries: use `@EntityGraph` or JPQL `JOIN FETCH`
- Use Flyway or Liquibase for database migrations

## Security
- Use Spring Security with `SecurityFilterChain` (not WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter)
- Use JWT for stateless API authentication
- Hash passwords with `BCryptPasswordEncoder`
- Use `@PreAuthorize` for method-level security
- Configure CORS for frontend origins

## Testing
- Use `@SpringBootTest` for integration tests
- Use `@WebMvcTest` for controller layer tests
- Use `@DataJpaTest` for repository tests
- Use Testcontainers for database integration tests
- Mock dependencies with `@MockBean`
